I have an idea we can all work on. Right now I have a half-finished iOS app called "U.S. History Hunter" (it's on my repo). 
I've taken a spreadsheet from the official Registered U.S. Landmarks site and parsed all the information into JSON. Then I used a tool that returns all coordinates of those landmarks and linked them up with X-Code's map-view API. What we can do is put the information on a server instead of having it local in the compiled program. And then create an automation to update the info on the server when're there a change. That way whenever it updates we can have it push the information to the mobile app as well as a web application. 
Thoughts?

Tim Britton: 
studying algorithms isn't gonna help you get an SRE job. 
you should do some, but mainly just simple stuff. strings (palindromes, anagrams, etc), basic data structure stuff but nothing fancier than linked lists tbh
but you need to know the OSI levels, the whole 'what happens when you type google in a browser' you should be able to recite with your eyes closed
you need to know tcp vs udp, what dhcp is, how traceroute/ping works, how SSH/TLS works

suggestion: start with google in a browser. use tcpdump and wireshark to look at all the actual traffic down to the packet
And then write scripts with Puppet or Chef or whatever to automate them
And my biggest possible advice is to start a project now. Find something, anything you care about, that you can run on multiple servers with a database between them
